    "notes": "Western Punjabi written in Shahmukhi (Perso-Arabic/Nastaliq) script. Phonological system closely parallels Eastern Punjabi (Gurmukhi) but with stronger Persian/Arabic lexical stratum introducing /f q x ɣ z ʒ/. Do-chashmi-he (ھ) marks aspiration and breathy voice in native vocabulary, but historically voiced aspirates (e.g. بھ bh, جھ jh, ڈھ ɖh, دھ dh, گھ gh) have undergone tonal split in Punjabi: word-initial position yields a plain obstruent plus low or falling tone, not true murmured phonation. The orthography retains the aspiration digraph for etymological reasons. Tonal system: Punjabi has three contrastive tones — high/rising (historically from voiceless aspirated onsets), low/falling (historically from voiced aspirated onsets), and level/mid (default). Tone is not written in Shahmukhi. Retroflex stop ڑ (ɖ) is distinct from dental د (d̪) and is used for native Punjabi retroflexes. Nun-ghunna ں (̃) marks nasalisation of the preceding vowel.",
